00:07:41,015 --> 00:07:42,357
I'm actually impressed we have someone.

144
00:07:43,357 --> 00:07:45,799
So Trafidata was a small company from Seattle, Washington

145
00:07:46,400 --> 00:07:49,583
formed in 1972 to analyze traffic patterns.

146
00:07:50,844 --> 00:07:53,606
Founding members Paul Allen and Bill Gates

147
00:07:54,126 --> 00:07:57,209
would go on to combine their passion for microprocessors

148
00:07:57,369 --> 00:07:59,991
and software to grow their partnership

149
00:08:00,071 --> 00:08:01,933
into a slightly larger company that I'm

150
00:08:02,013 --> 00:08:03,194
sure you've heard of today.

151
00:08:04,735 --> 00:08:07,157
Is anyone familiar with the Homebrew Computer Club?

152
00:08:08,161 --> 00:08:11,442
probably a few more, yeah. So this was Gordon French, invited

153
00:08:11,462 --> 00:08:14,463
some of his friends over to his house in 1975, they just decided

154
00:08:14,483 --> 00:08:17,184
to geek out and talk about computers for a bit. But the

155
00:08:17,824 --> 00:08:21,625
club grew, attracted people from all over Silicon Valley, until

156
00:08:21,786 --> 00:08:26,627
one day, two of its members, Steve Wozniak and Steve Jobs,

157
00:08:27,207 --> 00:08:29,668
put their heads together and decided to build something.

158
00:08:30,789 --> 00:08:34,550
Needless to say, their creation, the Apple computer, impressed

159
00:08:34,590 --> 00:08:37,851
the club and a few other billion people around the world.

160
00:08:39,110 --> 00:08:41,550
And I'll be impressed if anyone knows who this is.

161
00:08:44,051 --> 00:08:45,712
No hands, awesome.

162
00:08:45,732 --> 00:08:48,892
Small boy, 1982 in Potomac, Maryland,

163
00:08:49,213 --> 00:08:51,273
filled his parents' basement with a bunch of computers

164
00:08:51,673 --> 00:08:52,914
and set out to make something.

165
00:08:53,994 --> 00:08:55,114
He tried and tried and tried.

166
