10 years later, he released his first shareware game

167
00:08:58,095 --> 00:08:58,515
called ZZT.

168
00:08:59,930 --> 00:09:02,212
This is Tim Sweeney, now a young man.

169
00:09:02,232 --> 00:09:05,215
He didn't want people to know that he was just working out

170
00:09:05,255 --> 00:09:06,196
of his parents' basement.

171
00:09:06,617 --> 00:09:08,658
So he came up with two really big words

172
00:09:08,719 --> 00:09:12,402
and crammed them together to make his company Epic MegaGames.

173
00:09:14,204 --> 00:09:16,866
As the company grew, it had a few successes along the way.

174
00:09:17,387 --> 00:09:19,328
And since, we have been fortunate enough

175
00:09:19,408 --> 00:09:21,190
to grow into an international business.

176
00:09:22,972 --> 00:09:24,413
So why am I talking about all this?

177
00:09:25,614 --> 00:09:30,456
How could you have looked at these teams and determined beforehand if they would have been a success?

178
00:09:30,876 --> 00:09:32,977
If you could have put a magic band on their lives,

179
00:09:33,637 --> 00:09:37,078
what patterns could you have found and recreated to ensure your own success?

180
00:09:38,719 --> 00:09:40,840
If only it were that simple, we'd all be doing it.

181
00:09:41,240 --> 00:09:43,581
There is no formula that can predict success.

182
00:09:43,801 --> 00:09:45,722
Analytics aren't magic bands.

183
00:09:46,142 --> 00:09:47,782
They simply don't work that way.

184
00:09:48,122 --> 00:09:52,084
It's not like these teams just sprouted out of Zeus's head, emerging as gods.

185
00:09:53,501 --> 00:09:57,283
They each had their share of both success and failure along the way.

186
00:09:58,064 --> 00:10:02,366
What set them apart was that they were driven by their passion to learn from those mistakes

187
00:10:02,686 --> 00:10:03,547
and try again.

188
00:10:04,328 --> 00:10:07,010
It's a great lesson, something we should all do in our lives,

189
00:10:07,070 --> 00:10:07,490
for sure.

190
00:10:07,871 --> 00:10:10,412
It's also a big part of iterative design, which

191
00:10:10,452 --> 00:10:13,134
we've talked about a lot today, and coincidentally,

192
00:10:13,614 --> 00:10:15,695
is the very foundation for analytics.

193
00:10:16,416 --> 00:10:19,758
You make a hypothesis, you gather data, and then you test.

194
00:10:20,438 --> 00:10:22,359
And through an understanding of the failures

195
00:10:22,419 --> 00:10:25,681
of that hypothesis, you form a new one, you retest,

196
00:10:25,801 --> 00:10:29,283
and ideally, improve your outcome every time you cycle.

197
00:10:30,015 --> 00:10:34,757
The goal of analytics is what's called improving your probability space over time.

198
00:10:35,558 --> 00:10:39,479
If it were simple as looking at a bunch of numbers and reading answers,

199
00:10:39,740 --> 00:10:41,220
we wouldn't be having this conversation.

200
00:10:42,541 --> 00:10:43,981
So, here is a great example.

201
00:10:44,442 --> 00:10:47,243
This chart shows a list of the top 25 games of 2011.

202
00:10:47,283 --> 00:10:49,464
It's like 18 months ago.

203
00:10:50,884 --> 00:10:53,906
The games with the blue popularity were all very successful games.

204
00:10:54,386 --> 00:10:56,066
They were good, they were profitable.

205
00:10:56,715 --> 00:11:00,555
the games with green in their popularity were mega hits.

206
00:11:00,855 --> 00:11:04,376
They were profitable on a scale 10 to 100 times that

207
00:11:05,036 --> 00:11:05,736
of the blue games.

208
00:11:07,137 --> 00:11:08,517
So the question then is,

209
00:11:09,197 --> 00:11:10,897
what separates the blue from the green?

210
00:11:10,977 --> 00:11:12,558
How do you get your game to cross over

211
00:11:12,958 --> 00:11:14,718
from a blue game to a green game?

212
00:11:15,918 --> 00:11:17,859
The simple assumption is that the green games

213
00:11:18,399 --> 00:11:19,139
are better games.

214
00:11:19,979 --> 00:11:20,659
And if that's true,

215
00:11:21,059 --> 00:11:23,220
their review scores should reflect that, right?

216
00:11:24,511 --> 00:11:26,092
Not really, it's kind of all over the board.

217
00:11:26,672 --> 00:11:28,674
It's not to say that quality isn't important.

218
00:11:29,074 --> 00:11:30,855
These were all pretty well-reviewed games,

219
00:11:30,895 --> 00:11:31,996
they were all fun games,

220
00:11:32,296 --> 00:11:35,098
but beyond a base threshold of acceptable quality,

221
00:11:35,718 --> 00:11:38,580
score becomes a somewhat meaningless statistic.

222
00:11:39,961 --> 00:11:42,722
And remember, I said it's not always just about money.

223
00:11:43,383 --> 00:11:45,924
You need to create a meaningful experience for your players.

224
00:11:46,825 --> 00:11:48,126
So rather than review score,

225
00:11:48,706 --> 00:11:52,048
look at how much time people spent playing these games.

226
00:11:53,476 --> 00:11:55,678
That's a little bit stronger of a correlation.

227
00:11:56,819 --> 00:12:00,243
So while baseline quality is obviously important,

228
00:12:03,225 --> 00:12:05,728
a more significant factor of success

229
00:12:05,868 --> 00:12:08,030
might be how to keep your players engaged.

230
00:12:08,791 --> 00:12:10,312
Again, this doesn't give you any answers.

231
00:12:10,413 --> 00:12:11,954
It just leads to the next question

232
00:12:12,014 --> 00:12:13,716
was, how do you accomplish that?

233
00:12:14,738 --> 00:12:19,342
And to be perfectly clear, I don't expect you to take anything away from the results of this particular study.

234
00:12:19,903 --> 00:12:24,106
I'm simply trying to show you that my initial assumptions,

235
00:12:24,186 --> 00:12:27,909
what I would actually say are pretty common assumptions, were incorrect.

236
00:12:28,550 --> 00:12:33,314
And as I drilled down deeper, I didn't necessarily find any answers, only more questions.

237
00:12:33,834 --> 00:12:37,257
I had to cycle and improve my probability space over time.

238
00:12:37,938 --> 00:12:39,919
Assumptions just weren't enough.

239
00:12:41,415 --> 00:12:44,235
But just having mountains of data isn't useful.

240
00:12:44,295 --> 00:12:46,356
You need to actually do something with it, right?

241
00:12:46,736 --> 00:12:48,897
So really, we're looking at a three-step process here.

242
