Now, everyone knows that gamers are like geeky teenage boys,

271
00:14:15,779 --> 00:14:15,979
right?

272
00:14:17,260 --> 00:14:19,202
Except that this data says otherwise.

273
00:14:20,303 --> 00:14:21,604
So take one last look at that chart.

274
00:14:23,123 --> 00:14:26,866
And then let's look at the four most popular games

275
00:14:27,026 --> 00:14:27,946
in the world today.

276
00:14:29,267 --> 00:14:31,608
Can you guess which games they are based just

277
00:14:31,828 --> 00:14:32,789
off the demographics?

278
00:14:34,170 --> 00:14:38,652
This one is possibly, probably, is the most popular game

279
00:14:38,692 --> 00:14:39,492
in the world right now.

280
00:14:40,133 --> 00:14:41,494
Note that the bulk of the players

281
00:14:41,534 --> 00:14:43,074
are women over 35 years old.

282
00:14:43,715 --> 00:14:45,075
Anyone have a guess as to what it might be?

283
00:14:45,096 --> 00:14:48,237
You're all on target.

284
00:14:48,257 --> 00:14:49,078
You're all on target.

285
00:14:50,518 --> 00:14:51,299
All right, number two.

286
00:14:52,408 --> 00:14:58,132
Massively male audience, bulk of whom is around 18 years old. We're probably looking at a shooter game. Any thoughts?

287
00:15:03,877 --> 00:15:05,098
And note, note,

288
00:15:05,699 --> 00:15:10,903
bulk of the users are 18 years old and older. This is not necessarily a kids game.

289
00:15:11,944 --> 00:15:14,526
All right, so this one massively male audience,

290
00:15:15,346 --> 00:15:18,629
slightly older than Minecraft. Any thoughts on what this one might be?

291
00:15:22,200 --> 00:15:24,221
Call of Duty, heard League of Legends, no.

292
00:15:24,961 --> 00:15:26,562
This is World of Warcraft.

293
00:15:26,862 --> 00:15:29,863
And again, not as female as most people

294
00:15:30,163 --> 00:15:31,104
would generally assume.

295
00:15:31,124 --> 00:15:33,365
All right, last one before we move on.

296
00:15:33,605 --> 00:15:35,926
Massively male audience, Scream Shooter, what is it?

297
00:15:38,387 --> 00:15:39,507
Nothing, nobody has a guess.

298
00:15:39,748 --> 00:15:40,968
I heard one person say Call of Duty,

299
00:15:41,428 --> 00:15:42,129
so I'll give it away.

300
00:15:42,149 --> 00:15:43,849
It is not, it is League of Legends.

301
00:15:45,030 --> 00:15:46,431
None of these games are shooters.

302
00:15:46,471 --> 00:15:48,051
The most popular games in the world

303
00:15:48,111 --> 00:15:49,772
are shooters played by teenage boys, right?

304
00:15:50,705 --> 00:15:51,205
Not at all.

305
00:15:51,765 --> 00:15:53,346
And then take another look.

306
00:15:54,207 --> 00:15:56,168
Not a single one of those matches up

307
00:15:56,288 --> 00:15:58,850
with the general data of who plays games.

308
00:15:59,270 --> 00:16:01,852
If you had used that data to inform whatever

309
00:16:01,892 --> 00:16:05,214
it was you were building, you would have been way off base.

310
00:16:06,555 --> 00:16:08,397
And here's where I melt your brain even a little bit more.

311
00:16:09,517 --> 00:16:11,459
Not a single one of those charts is accurate.

312
00:16:11,659 --> 00:16:12,760
They're all wrong.

313
00:16:13,400 --> 00:16:14,761
Because it's never that simple, right?

314
00:16:15,201 --> 00:16:18,463
All of this data is self-reported, which skews it.

315
00:16:19,075 --> 00:16:22,536
And it all comes from Facebook, which biases the source.

316
00:16:23,457 --> 00:16:27,459
And I did this to show you that data by itself is meaningless.

317
00:16:28,059 --> 00:16:29,440
It's just information.

318
00:16:29,720 --> 00:16:32,161
It has to be processed, and it has to be interpreted.

319
00:16:32,461 --> 00:16:35,722
And it all comes down to how you decide to look at it.

320
00:16:37,263 --> 00:16:40,044
So data is objective, and it's factual.

321
00:16:40,625 --> 00:16:42,566
But its tangible connection to the real world

322
00:16:42,626 --> 00:16:44,747
is exactly what makes it interesting and easy

323
00:16:44,787 --> 00:16:45,467
to misinterpret.

324
00:16:46,189 --> 00:16:49,993
Every map that you create is just a collection of data points.

325
00:16:50,734 --> 00:16:53,418
But how many times have you heard about driving the narrative of your game

326
00:16:53,758 --> 00:16:56,301
or using it as a means of environmental storytelling?

327
00:16:57,122 --> 00:17:00,687
Intentionally or otherwise, every map tells a story.

328
00:17:01,593 --> 00:17:05,795
This is a map of a neighborhood in Raleigh, North Carolina, where I live.

329
00:17:06,335 --> 00:17:13,417
It's called Boylan Heights, from a cartographer named Dennis Wood, and he uses datasets to

330
00:17:13,457 --> 00:17:14,437
tell stories.

331
00:17:15,197 --> 00:17:19,158
He says that maps exhibit and promote a political orientation.

332
00:17:19,698 --> 00:17:22,159
They're about something, and they have an agenda.

333
00:17:23,284 --> 00:17:25,425
As an example, here's another one of his maps

334
00:17:25,525 --> 00:17:27,005
overlaid on top of the original.

335
00:17:27,425 --> 00:17:30,226
And rather than houses, this one shows the distribution

336
00:17:30,346 --> 00:17:32,407
of power lines in that same neighborhood.

337
00:17:33,547 --> 00:17:33,867
OK.

338
00:17:34,427 --> 00:17:37,068
And now here's a third one that shows

339
00:17:37,588 --> 00:17:40,029
the trees in his neighborhood.

340
00:17:44,130 --> 00:17:45,391
And did that switch?

341
00:17:45,851 --> 00:17:46,171
It did.

342
00:17:46,371 --> 00:17:47,251
Why didn't it switch here?

343
00:17:51,473 --> 00:17:51,893
There we go.

344
00:17:52,748 --> 00:17:57,592
All right, so individually, each of these maps is just aggregated data.

345
00:17:58,212 --> 00:18:01,595
But viewed together, they start to establish a narrative.

346
00:18:02,195 --> 00:18:05,898
It talks about urban sprawl, expansion, and encroachment.

347
00:18:07,099 --> 00:18:10,582
Again, maybe that's how you might interpret that narrative,

348
00:18:10,622 --> 00:18:13,944
and probably that's what he wants you to build as a narrative.

349
00:18:14,527 --> 00:18:18,550
But the reality is you can't say for sure, because data is just information.

350
00:18:18,590 --> 00:18:19,830
There are no answers there.

351
00:18:20,291 --> 00:18:21,631
Wood hasn't written anything.

352
00:18:22,212 --> 00:18:23,753
He hasn't made any statements.

353
00:18:24,213 --> 00:18:27,755
But he's used raw data to make a social commentary.

354
00:18:28,415 --> 00:18:32,998
So the lesson to remember here is that everything that you do in your map, even the very act

355
00:18:33,058 --> 00:18:36,320
of you being the one who creates it, tells a story.

356
00:18:36,920 --> 00:18:40,282
And that's especially true when it's viewed in context.

357
00:18:42,000 --> 00:18:48,105
Now some companies like Google and Valve rely very heavily on data to drive their decision-making process.

358
00:18:48,685 --> 00:18:53,169
At their recent Steam Developers Days, they discussed how, like many modern companies,

359
00:18:53,209 --> 00:18:56,632
they monitor everything that goes through the system, everything that goes across Steam.

360
00:18:57,072 --> 00:19:03,898
But Valve distinguishes themselves by making every bit of that data available to each and every one of their employees.

361
00:19:04,659 --> 00:19:11,503
And so anybody who wants to start a conversation or make an argument is actually encouraged to reference that data in support of their point,

362
00:19:12,044 --> 00:19:16,047
because an informed decision carries much more weight than a straight opinion.

363
00:19:16,847 --> 00:19:21,711
When a decision is made using data, there's less chance for a random outcome.

364
00:19:22,731 --> 00:19:25,954
But remember that data is only information out of context.

365
00:19:26,765 --> 00:19:29,727
So data should inform your decision-making process.

366
00:19:29,887 --> 00:19:31,148
It's the middle of the equation.

367
00:19:31,789 --> 00:19:36,553
But since it's only information, data alone should never make a decision for you.

368
00:19:37,634 --> 00:19:41,537
And this is where things get tricky, because you see data being used in the context of

369
00:19:41,597 --> 00:19:42,458
a social science.

370
00:19:42,878 --> 00:19:47,062
And in the social sciences, there are no hard and correct answers.

371
00:19:48,058 --> 00:19:50,959
So whenever you see data being presented in any visual format,

372
00:19:51,039 --> 00:19:52,920
any chart, any graph, anything like that,

373
00:19:53,380 --> 00:19:56,101
understand that you're seeing it through someone else's filter,

374
00:19:56,741 --> 00:19:58,362
often with their bias.

375
00:19:58,862 --> 00:20:00,883
This isn't something that people do maliciously or even

376
00:20:00,923 --> 00:20:01,523
intentionally.

377
00:20:01,923 --> 00:20:03,123
It's just human nature.

378
00:20:04,084 --> 00:20:06,025
Data can always tell you a story,

379
00:20:06,265 --> 00:20:09,446
but only if you try to interpret what that story is.

380
00:20:12,787 --> 00:20:14,528
So like many things in life, you have

381
00:20:14,568 --> 00:20:16,208
to start by asking questions.

382
00:20:17,296 --> 00:20:18,758
And this is where metrics come into play.

383
00:20:19,018 --> 00:20:20,460
And they can be absolutely useful,

384
00:20:20,820 --> 00:20:22,882
but you have to embrace and understand

385
00:20:22,902 --> 00:20:24,544
that they too are limited.

386
00:20:25,545 --> 00:20:29,670
Technically speaking, metrics is distance in metric space.

387
00:20:30,451 --> 00:20:31,912
It's just a measurement.

388
00:20:32,553 --> 00:20:34,615
All these charts and graphs can be very pretty

389
00:20:34,655 --> 00:20:35,797
and very interesting to look at.

390
00:20:36,527 --> 00:20:38,768
but they don't suggest change.

391
00:20:39,248 --> 00:20:42,389
They compare data or measure aggregates of data

392
00:20:42,549 --> 00:20:43,749
across different points.

393
00:20:44,490 --> 00:20:46,610
But it's just information for you to interpret.

394
00:20:47,090 --> 00:20:49,271
You need to provide that context.

395
00:20:49,811 --> 00:20:51,772
You need to use your design skills.

396
00:20:52,452 --> 00:20:54,533
And in order to get to the right answers,

397
00:20:54,733 --> 00:20:56,653
you need to ask the right questions.

398
00:20:57,761 --> 00:21:01,083
The level design team at Epic uses metrics in various ways.

399
00:21:01,484 --> 00:21:03,585
This is one example from Gears of War Judgment

400
00:21:03,905 --> 00:21:07,187
that shows how the game's, a couple of different levels,

401
00:21:07,247 --> 00:21:09,189
how their frame rate changed over time.

402
00:21:09,829 --> 00:21:11,991
And it's cool to see, you can see the line trends upward,

403
00:21:12,011 --> 00:21:13,371
which is exactly what you want, right?

404
00:21:14,772 --> 00:21:16,293
But once you have this kind of information,

405
00:21:16,434 --> 00:21:18,275
you really need to start questioning it.

406
00:21:19,275 --> 00:21:22,077
Does this data indicate that the map is getting better?

407
00:21:23,438 --> 00:21:24,679
Put the map aside for a moment.

408
00:21:25,468 --> 00:21:27,648
Did someone change something in the rendering pipeline?

409
00:21:28,129 --> 00:21:29,489
Has pathfinding been fixed?

410
00:21:29,909 --> 00:21:32,330
Have they fixed that quirky bug with the particle system?

411
00:21:32,970 --> 00:21:35,191
If you answer yes to any one of those questions,

412
00:21:35,471 --> 00:21:37,271
then your game and your level's frame rate

413
00:21:37,431 --> 00:21:41,793
is going to get up, even if the level itself is still

414
00:21:41,853 --> 00:21:43,953
just a huge, unpolished mess.

415
00:21:44,934 --> 00:21:48,075
These charts track change, but they don't

416
00:21:48,135 --> 00:21:50,115
say what caused that change.

417
00:21:50,975 --> 00:21:55,858
In order to figure out what was going on here, we had to dig and find more answers.

418
00:21:56,979 --> 00:22:03,322
Now here's another one that shows, uh, tracks deltas in population in our online servers.

419
00:22:03,902 --> 00:22:05,863
And the different colors represent different game types.

420
00:22:06,283 --> 00:22:11,326
And you can see here that there is a spike where people just suddenly stopped playing Execution,

421
00:22:11,446 --> 00:22:15,248
which was the number one game type, and then started playing a bunch of other stuff.

422
00:22:16,129 --> 00:22:16,669
So what happened?

423
00:22:17,564 --> 00:22:19,945
Well, you can infer that that change was due to a server

424
00:22:19,965 --> 00:22:20,345
reboot.

425
00:22:20,845 --> 00:22:24,006
And you might even look, and the time stamp on that

426
00:22:24,126 --> 00:22:27,187
might coincide with that change in population.

427
00:22:27,787 --> 00:22:28,467
But it's not enough.

428
00:22:28,968 --> 00:22:30,308
You have to question even deeper,

429
00:22:30,348 --> 00:22:32,189
because there's so many other factors that could

430
00:22:32,269 --> 00:22:33,469
influence a change like this.

431
00:22:34,609 --> 00:22:35,970
What day of the week are we talking about?

432
00:22:36,670 --> 00:22:37,350
Was it a weekend?

433
00:22:37,810 --> 00:22:39,511
Or were people going off to school?

434
00:22:40,291 --> 00:22:41,091
Was it a holiday?

435
00:22:41,572 --> 00:22:43,532
Was there some major news event in the world

436
00:22:43,572 --> 00:22:45,593
that pulled people away from gaming for a little bit?

437
00:22:46,255 --> 00:22:47,355
Who knows, at the end of the day,

438
00:22:47,375 --> 00:22:49,417
I have no idea what caused that spike.

439
00:22:49,857 --> 00:22:50,717
It just happened.

440
00:22:50,737 --> 00:22:53,639
It was just a random chart I just pulled off of our servers.

441
00:22:54,380 --> 00:22:57,341
I can't explain it, because this chart by itself

442
00:22:57,622 --> 00:22:58,902
isn't enough information.

443
00:23:00,023 --> 00:23:03,305
In all of these cases, metrics are your starting point.

444
00:23:03,785 --> 00:23:05,286
If you want to dive deeper, you need

445
00:23:05,326 --> 00:23:07,968
to account for those social science aspects of design.

446
00:23:08,448 --> 00:23:09,989
Get into the mind of your players

447
00:23:10,309 --> 00:23:13,251
and understand the reasons behind their actions.

448
00:23:15,033 --> 00:23:18,157
So a few years ago I did a talk about a map called Trenches.

449
00:23:18,697 --> 00:23:19,358
Is anybody there for that?

450
00:23:20,539 --> 00:23:22,001
Yeah, a couple people.

451
00:23:22,081 --> 00:23:26,987
Heatmap showed that players were only using one side of the map,

452
00:23:27,247 --> 00:23:29,009
and the other side was being completely ignored.

453
00:23:29,934 --> 00:23:34,460
We figured this was some artifact of player preference or player behavior,

454
00:23:35,061 --> 00:23:38,826
and so we just kind of pushed things around and didn't really deal with it.

455
00:23:38,886 --> 00:23:42,911
And then during the beta, this map was a complete and utter failure.

456
00:23:43,232 --> 00:23:45,414
People stopped playing the map almost entirely.

457
00:23:46,664 --> 00:23:48,825
And this was entirely our fault.

458
00:23:49,185 --> 00:23:52,426
We forgot that heat maps are just measurements.

459
00:23:52,767 --> 00:23:55,368
At no point did they imply why people

460
00:23:55,548 --> 00:23:57,068
were in those specific locations.

461
00:23:57,549 --> 00:23:59,830
They simply measured how many people were there

462
00:24:00,230 --> 00:24:01,110
and where they were.

463
00:24:01,710 --> 00:24:02,851
And since it did so poorly.

464
00:24:04,163 --> 00:24:06,285
We decided to look at that map again after the beta,

465
00:24:06,685 --> 00:24:08,587
and this time we went in objectively.

466
00:24:09,127 --> 00:24:12,250
And sure enough, we discovered that we had trapped players

467
00:24:12,350 --> 00:24:13,071
in their spawns.

468
00:24:13,611 --> 00:24:15,392
This was not player preference.

469
00:24:16,093 --> 00:24:18,755
When we fixed that problem, the real problem,

470
00:24:19,215 --> 00:24:22,218
the map went on to become one of our most successful maps ever.

471
00:24:23,826 --> 00:24:29,348
Now, this is exactly why you need to ask questions that explain your metrics.

472
00:24:29,869 --> 00:24:31,749
You need to stay honest and objective.

473
00:24:32,270 --> 00:24:34,791
Sometimes you fall in love with a design because it looks cool,

474
00:24:34,831 --> 00:24:37,112
or because, I mean, quite frankly, you built it, right?

475
00:24:37,212 --> 00:24:38,052
So it has to be good.

476
00:24:38,632 --> 00:24:41,674
When in reality, it may not be that great of a design.

477
00:24:42,374 --> 00:24:45,255
And when that happens, you run the risk of only seeing

478
00:24:45,295 --> 00:24:47,616
the data that supports your argument.

479
00:24:48,244 --> 00:24:52,868
This is one of the reasons that iteration and communication is so important.

480
00:24:53,408 --> 00:24:57,711
You need to establish your hypothesis, test, measure, and repeat.

481
00:24:58,152 --> 00:24:59,273
Question everything.

482
00:25:00,040 --> 00:25:02,220
You even need to question your questions.

483
00:25:02,700 --> 00:25:04,841
And what I mean by that is, ask yourself

484
00:25:05,341 --> 00:25:07,281
why you want to know to begin with.

485
00:25:07,861 --> 00:25:10,562
Are you expecting a specific answer when you ask a question?

486
00:25:11,122 --> 00:25:13,382
If you are, then you have to be especially careful

487
00:25:13,682 --> 00:25:16,503
not to bias that question by leading the results

488
00:25:16,863 --> 00:25:18,363
to your expected answer.

489
00:25:19,903 --> 00:25:21,323
And this is where we failed in trenches.

490
00:25:21,663 --> 00:25:24,984
We used heat maps to justify our design decisions

491
00:25:25,424 --> 00:25:27,604
rather than looking at it as just information

492
00:25:27,985 --> 00:25:28,905
leading to a solution.

493
00:25:30,023 --> 00:25:34,867
And then, once you do have answers, it's pretty safe to start questioning those as well.

494
00:25:35,907 --> 00:25:38,769
Is that answer an actionable item?

495
00:25:39,710 --> 00:25:42,352
Remember, your curiosity here isn't what you're important.

496
00:25:42,392 --> 00:25:43,632
That's not why you're doing this.

497
00:25:43,993 --> 00:25:46,895
Your goal should always be meaningful change.

498
00:25:48,687 --> 00:25:51,609
And since metrics don't provide you with answers,

499
00:25:52,110 --> 00:25:54,131
but what does make them special

500
00:25:54,312 --> 00:25:56,813
is that they help you identify the important questions.

501
00:25:57,334 --> 00:25:59,716
And questions are what force you to be objective,

502
00:26:00,036 --> 00:26:02,038
to think outside the box and look at your work

503
00:26:02,258 --> 00:26:03,699
from a unique perspective.

504
00:26:04,399 --> 00:26:07,342
And the why is the most important thing you can ask.

505
00:26:08,102 --> 00:26:09,924
Why was the frame rate low in those charts?

506
00:26:10,464 --> 00:26:12,125
Why did the population numbers fall?

507
00:26:12,666 --> 00:26:15,068
Why were players on only one side of the map?

508
00:26:15,694 --> 00:26:18,737
And the most important why of all, and I can't stress this enough,

509
00:26:19,278 --> 00:26:22,702
is to ask yourself, why do you want to know the answer?

510
00:26:24,804 --> 00:26:27,327
So in the trenches map, we failed to ask why.

511
00:26:29,936 --> 00:26:32,217
We were looking for answers that justified our assumptions

512
00:26:32,517 --> 00:26:34,338
without even really understanding what the hell it

513
00:26:34,358 --> 00:26:35,339
was we were looking for.

514
00:26:35,939 --> 00:26:38,520
But we did learn a valuable lesson.

515
00:26:39,040 --> 00:26:41,462
And when a similar problem popped up in a different map,

516
00:26:41,882 --> 00:26:43,062
we handled it quite differently.

517
00:26:43,763 --> 00:26:47,164
This is Academy, which was from a later Gears DLC.

518
00:26:47,565 --> 00:26:49,666
And it had this round area in the middle of the map

519
00:26:50,006 --> 00:26:53,027
that was elevated with very tight and controllable

520
00:26:53,127 --> 00:26:56,429
entrances, and lots of cover leading up to those entrances.

521
00:26:57,877 --> 00:27:01,337
And of course, Heatmap showed an incredible accumulation

522
00:27:01,557 --> 00:27:04,298
of movement and death all in this one spot,

523
00:27:04,758 --> 00:27:06,299
while the rest of the map was being ignored.

524
00:27:06,319 --> 00:27:07,739
Sound familiar?

525
00:27:08,599 --> 00:27:11,060
So we wanted to figure out why.

526
00:27:12,520 --> 00:27:14,640
We had some ideas, but rather than just assuming

527
00:27:14,680 --> 00:27:15,681
we knew what the problem was,

528
00:27:16,041 --> 00:27:17,861
we approached it objectively.

529
00:27:18,401 --> 00:27:20,962
We looked at how players were dying, not just where,

530
00:27:21,742 --> 00:27:22,882
where they were in cover,

531
00:27:23,182 --> 00:27:25,043
and why they were there to begin with.

532
00:27:25,570 --> 00:27:30,592
And what we were able to determine was that teams would charge into this area to get the boom shot,

533
00:27:30,872 --> 00:27:33,733
which is arguably the most powerful weapon in any Gears game.

534
00:27:34,513 --> 00:27:35,754
And then they would just camp there.

535
00:27:36,314 --> 00:27:38,675
And as they camp there, more and more people would run up there,

536
00:27:39,035 --> 00:27:42,777
and since they had the most powerful weapon in the game, they would kill them over and over and over.

537
00:27:43,237 --> 00:27:45,878
So why would you ever leave, right? You had the power spot in the map.

538
00:27:47,078 --> 00:27:51,780
So, to fix it, we moved the boom shot to the far opposite end of the map.

539
00:27:52,735 --> 00:27:53,916
And then we continued to test.

540
00:27:54,276 --> 00:27:56,377
And we saw a dramatic shift in player movement

541
00:27:56,537 --> 00:27:57,998
away from this one area.

542
00:27:58,719 --> 00:28:01,020
The new results fell much more in line

543
00:28:01,040 --> 00:28:03,081
with what we expected and hoped to see.

544
00:28:03,661 --> 00:28:06,643
We were able to say, hey, this was a fixed problem,

545
00:28:06,703 --> 00:28:08,284
and it was high fives all around.

546
00:28:10,245 --> 00:28:13,127
Until people started dying in the spot

547
00:28:13,227 --> 00:28:14,708
where we moved the boom shot to.

548
00:28:15,808 --> 00:28:17,569
All of this data was telling us was

549
00:28:17,609 --> 00:28:20,591
that everywhere we put the boom shot, people were going to die.

550
00:28:22,871 --> 00:28:25,331
And this is exactly where our previous lesson came into play.

551
00:28:25,992 --> 00:28:27,212
Question everything.

552
00:28:27,512 --> 00:28:28,432
Ask why.

553
00:28:29,232 --> 00:28:32,033
Why were players dying in this spot?

554
00:28:32,653 --> 00:28:34,413
Remember, once you have your hypothesis,

555
00:28:34,453 --> 00:28:36,774
you need to test it, find the failures,

556
00:28:37,054 --> 00:28:39,314
and then formulate a new hypothesis

557
00:28:39,414 --> 00:28:41,055
based on the current results.

558
00:28:41,715 --> 00:28:43,695
Just because the answer to the previous why

559
00:28:43,795 --> 00:28:45,715
was people were dying because of the boom shot,

560
00:28:46,216 --> 00:28:48,456
that didn't mean it was the same answer

561
00:28:48,776 --> 00:28:50,917
to this question right now.

562
00:28:52,901 --> 00:28:55,584
So we set all that boomshot data aside and we started from scratch.

563
00:28:56,365 --> 00:28:59,669
And here's a screenshot of that same area from a slightly different camera angle.

564
00:29:00,310 --> 00:29:03,914
And it turns out that people were abusing their over-the-camera shoulder

565
00:29:04,094 --> 00:29:06,437
and had a line-of-sight advantage right by that arrow.

566
00:29:06,457 --> 00:29:06,497
So...

567
00:29:09,523 --> 00:29:12,064
we didn't know at first why that happened.

568
00:29:12,504 --> 00:29:13,784
So we went back and looked,

569
00:29:13,964 --> 00:29:15,745
and all of our previous testing had been done

570
00:29:16,065 --> 00:29:17,945
when the map was an undecorated shell.

571
00:29:18,365 --> 00:29:20,166
And if you watch right by where the arrow is,

572
00:29:20,446 --> 00:29:22,387
you'll see that the walls in that version

573
00:29:22,547 --> 00:29:23,707
were significantly higher.

574
00:29:24,467 --> 00:29:25,848
And so when the map was decorated,

575
00:29:26,168 --> 00:29:28,068
and those walls were inadvertently lowered,

576
00:29:29,209 --> 00:29:31,669
it opened up a line of sight that didn't previously exist.

577
00:29:32,530 --> 00:29:34,990
So we simply just filled that space back in.

578
00:29:35,010 --> 00:29:36,831
The more we tested,

579
00:29:37,747 --> 00:29:45,213
Sure enough, everything fell into line, heat maps started to show a nice distribution of deaths all across the map, and everything was golden.

580
00:29:47,174 --> 00:29:52,238
We knew, based off of what we had in trenches, that we had to look at these as two separate problems.

581
00:29:52,639 --> 00:29:56,882
There was a correlation to the boomshot moving, but there was no causation.

582
00:29:57,422 --> 00:30:03,046
You have to resist the urge to be satisfied with the status quo, and always remember to question everything.

583
00:30:03,790 --> 00:30:08,958
Alright, so data is information, metrics are measurements, comparisons of that information,

584
00:30:09,980 --> 00:30:14,888
analytics, and this is the meat of the thing, are used to interpret that information.

585
00:30:16,479 --> 00:30:19,080
And analytics and metrics are very often confused,

586
00:30:19,100 --> 00:30:21,462
but they have some very, very distinct differences.

587
00:30:22,663 --> 00:30:24,705
Metrics is math-based.

588
00:30:24,965 --> 00:30:27,407
It's hard science versus analytics,

589
00:30:27,527 --> 00:30:29,788
which, and this is a little bit controversial to some people,

590
00:30:30,369 --> 00:30:33,151
is a social science that doesn't necessarily

591
00:30:33,311 --> 00:30:35,332
imply a real, true answer.

592
00:30:35,372 --> 00:30:38,234
It's something that you have to interpret or infer

593
00:30:38,374 --> 00:30:40,776
into the future versus metrics, which

594
00:30:40,836 --> 00:30:42,017
is a measurement of past data.

595
00:30:43,435 --> 00:30:45,216
Really, analytics has two functions.

596
00:30:45,876 --> 00:30:49,418
First, you use data analysis to gain insight.

597
00:30:50,058 --> 00:30:53,600
And the goal there is to separate fact from opinion.

598
00:30:54,540 --> 00:30:55,440
Everyone has opinions.

599
00:30:55,500 --> 00:30:57,761
And so it can be impossible to ever decide,

600
00:30:58,021 --> 00:31:00,602
when you have two conflicting opinions, which one is right.

601
00:31:01,283 --> 00:31:02,823
And opinions lead to arguments.

602
00:31:03,184 --> 00:31:05,525
And that can create unresolvable conflict.

603
00:31:06,416 --> 00:31:12,138
So in order to prevent yourself from just aimlessly spinning on and on forever,

604
00:31:12,698 --> 00:31:16,900
you need to look at the facts and see how they relate to the team's common goal.

605
00:31:18,320 --> 00:31:22,342
It makes sense. If you don't have a finish line, you're never going to get there.

606
00:31:23,062 --> 00:31:27,144
If you don't have a starting point and a finish line, then there's nothing to measure.

607
00:31:27,804 --> 00:31:29,365
So before you start anything...

608
00:31:30,382 --> 00:31:33,623
outline your goals, and define your success state.

609
00:31:34,403 --> 00:31:36,864
The purpose of analytics isn't just to impress people

610
00:31:36,924 --> 00:31:39,125
with pretty charts and mountains of numbers.

611
00:31:40,145 --> 00:31:42,326
You need to separate facts from opinions

612
00:31:42,646 --> 00:31:45,948
and then use those facts to help you understand

613
00:31:46,268 --> 00:31:47,969
what's going on in your maps.

614
00:31:48,649 --> 00:31:50,850
And this is the second major function of analytics,

615
00:31:51,510 --> 00:31:53,691
using those facts to guide decision making.

616
00:31:54,456 --> 00:31:56,678
If your goals are outlined before you start,

617
00:31:57,178 --> 00:32:00,642
then they can be used to inform your process rather than

618
00:32:00,662 --> 00:32:03,925
the result. This makes you proactive rather than

619
00:32:03,965 --> 00:32:04,605
reactionary.

620
00:32:05,526 --> 00:32:07,328
Go back to the beginning of my talk, and what were the

621
00:32:07,368 --> 00:32:09,410
three things I wanted to talk about?

622
00:32:09,630 --> 00:32:12,813
Ask what you're building, why you're building it, and who

623
00:32:12,853 --> 00:32:16,736
you're building it for. Those answers define your goals.

624
00:32:17,197 --> 00:32:18,318
And if you stick to them,

625
00:32:19,006 --> 00:32:20,907
you can tell when change in your map

626
00:32:21,247 --> 00:32:23,908
is actually going to be something meaningful

627
00:32:24,329 --> 00:32:25,829
rather than just decorative.

628
00:32:27,670 --> 00:32:30,092
Outlining your goals helps keep you focused.

629
00:32:30,692 --> 00:32:32,293
There's less chance you'll be distracted

630
00:32:32,393 --> 00:32:34,434
by misleading information.

631
00:32:34,994 --> 00:32:36,195
You have to be especially careful

632
00:32:36,275 --> 00:32:37,776
of really good presentations

633
00:32:38,096 --> 00:32:40,417
because visualization can be very important,

634
00:32:41,237 --> 00:32:43,939
but remember those maps of the Boylan Heights neighborhood?

635
00:32:44,279 --> 00:32:47,641
The visualization didn't necessarily explain anything at all.

636
00:32:48,530 --> 00:32:51,592
Analytics is all about patterns, and our brains love patterns.

637
00:32:52,793 --> 00:32:56,295
We have this kind of inherent need to explain patterns.

638
00:32:56,875 --> 00:32:59,737
So you see a pie chart, and your brain veers off to thoughts,

639
00:32:59,918 --> 00:33:02,599
Pac-Man, and you end up chasing ghosts.

640
00:33:03,320 --> 00:33:07,323
Charts can mislead you to believe that false information is real,

641
00:33:07,643 --> 00:33:10,004
like seeing deaths due to boomshot in Academy,

642
00:33:10,285 --> 00:33:13,106
when really, there is no deaths due to boomshot in Academy.

643
00:33:13,899 --> 00:33:16,942
Or think about those player charts that I showed you in the very beginning of the talk,

644
00:33:17,302 --> 00:33:22,187
and how if you had used them to inform your design process, you would have been so far off base.

645
00:33:22,888 --> 00:33:26,491
This is why some people call data visualization a halfway house.

646
00:33:27,112 --> 00:33:31,616
It's that middle point, it's the stopping point from data to decision.

647
00:33:32,296 --> 00:33:34,619
And remember my Steam slide, there it is right in the middle.

648
00:33:34,979 --> 00:33:39,583
It isn't answers, it helps, analytics help guide you toward a decision.

649
00:33:41,379 --> 00:33:44,382
All right, and this is exactly where you come into the picture designer.

650
00:33:44,662 --> 00:33:47,124
Take all those pretty charts and all that information

651
00:33:47,404 --> 00:33:51,027
and fold it into your knowledge and your design sensibilities.

652
00:33:51,568 --> 00:33:53,910
By combining your instincts with data,

653
00:33:54,270 --> 00:33:57,873
you go beyond functional solutions into something that can become

654
00:33:58,294 --> 00:34:03,118
emotionally resonant, that enables your players to make those connections

655
00:34:03,618 --> 00:34:06,060
with your game, with your level, and with your work.

656
00:34:07,380 --> 00:34:11,261
This is how you ask or how you answer what, why, and who.

657
00:34:11,982 --> 00:34:14,182
And this is a very specific skill set

658
00:34:14,482 --> 00:34:16,623
that distinguishes a designer on the team

659
00:34:17,183 --> 00:34:19,324
from everybody else who contributes to design

660
00:34:19,624 --> 00:34:21,004
by offering their opinions.

661
00:34:22,865 --> 00:34:25,946
Everyone has opinions and ideas, but not everyone

662
00:34:26,006 --> 00:34:30,067
understands the importance of how and when to actually make

663
00:34:30,167 --> 00:34:32,988
changes and how to make that change meaningful.

664
00:34:34,348 --> 00:34:36,068
Does anyone use Spotify or Pandora?

665
00:34:38,677 --> 00:34:39,818
Cool. So most of you know what they are.

666
00:34:39,878 --> 00:34:43,519
They use algorithms to predict what music you might like to listen to

667
00:34:43,639 --> 00:34:45,140
based off your basic listening patterns.

668
00:34:46,040 --> 00:34:47,701
And for the most part, they are pretty accurate.

669
00:34:48,381 --> 00:34:50,122
But to make a playlist that's really good,

670
00:34:50,782 --> 00:34:52,463
one that I really care about,

671
00:34:53,724 --> 00:34:56,485
still requires human input into the process.

672
00:34:57,085 --> 00:34:59,967
You have to go through and thumb up and thumb down those songs

673
00:35:00,327 --> 00:35:03,848
to get beyond just a list of computer-generated suggestions.

674
00:35:04,567 --> 00:35:06,467
Data only gets them halfway there.

675
00:35:06,768 --> 00:35:08,588
It still requires that human input

676
00:35:08,628 --> 00:35:11,010
to get from predictive to meaningful.

677
00:35:12,290 --> 00:35:17,413
Now, Netflix has a similar system on television and movies,

678
00:35:17,813 --> 00:35:19,193
but they've taken it one step further.

679
00:35:19,794 --> 00:35:22,435
Again, data can't tell them how to make a TV show,

680
00:35:22,775 --> 00:35:25,196
but they think it can tell them what they should be making.

681
00:35:26,057 --> 00:35:27,577
When they created House of Cards,

682
00:35:28,118 --> 00:35:30,218
they weren't just guessing at what people wanted,

683
00:35:30,559 --> 00:35:32,560
they were analyzing patterns in their database.

684
00:35:33,507 --> 00:35:34,768
So what do those patterns reveal?

685
00:35:36,670 --> 00:35:37,771
The Perry Mason effect.

686
00:35:39,372 --> 00:35:42,334
What would you guess is the most popular show

687
00:35:42,394 --> 00:35:43,695
streaming across Netflix?

688
00:35:45,617 --> 00:35:46,137
Perry Mason.

689
00:35:46,838 --> 00:35:50,260
Who are the most popular actors on everything viewed on Netflix?

690
00:35:51,661 --> 00:35:52,822
The actors from Perry Mason.

691
00:35:53,663 --> 00:35:54,784
OK, let's get abstract.

692
00:35:54,824 --> 00:35:57,226
If you look at just the themes of the shows

693
00:35:57,346 --> 00:35:59,708
across all the shows that are being streamed on Netflix,

694
00:36:00,188 --> 00:36:01,989
what comes up as the top list of themes?

695
00:36:03,204 --> 00:36:06,585
those viewed in Perry Mason. All the data that they had

696
00:36:06,665 --> 00:36:11,107
suggested that they should be remaking Perry Mason. So why

697
00:36:11,147 --> 00:36:15,708
did they make House of Cards? As an individual data point,

698
00:36:16,148 --> 00:36:19,950
Perry Mason is meaningless. Netflix calls this a ghost in

699
00:36:19,970 --> 00:36:23,971
the machine. It's a byproduct of complexity. In slightly more

700
00:36:24,051 --> 00:36:26,992
technical terms, as you increase the number of variables that

701
00:36:27,012 --> 00:36:30,433
you're measuring, you increase the odds of a false positive

702
00:36:30,493 --> 00:36:30,813
result.

703
00:36:31,695 --> 00:36:36,217
In any system, there's always the chance that some of your results will come back as being

704
00:36:36,317 --> 00:36:40,538
statistically significant, even if they're totally fake or wrong.

705
00:36:41,598 --> 00:36:47,460
Someone at some point is always going to camp at that boom shot location in Academy.

706
00:36:47,800 --> 00:36:48,761
That's just human nature.

707
00:36:49,081 --> 00:36:51,802
And anyone could suggest a change to make them move.

708
00:36:52,642 --> 00:36:56,563
But it's the designer's job to question why they were camping there.

709
00:36:57,363 --> 00:36:59,204
Why did Perry Mason show up?

710
00:37:01,362 --> 00:37:05,023
because that was a playlist generated by algorithm,

711
00:37:05,364 --> 00:37:06,804
with no one to thumb it up or down.

712
00:37:07,685 --> 00:37:10,426
I can look at any Call of Duty map or any popular map

713
00:37:10,466 --> 00:37:13,707
from any game, deconstruct the technical aspects of it,

714
00:37:14,248 --> 00:37:16,769
go through everything in there, and then recreate it.

715
00:37:17,709 --> 00:37:20,131
But is my new version going to be a success?

716
00:37:20,391 --> 00:37:22,091
Is it going to be emotionally resonant?

717
00:37:22,832 --> 00:37:24,773
Or is it just going to be a copycat?

718
00:37:25,777 --> 00:37:27,018
If you're looking at a bunch of data,

719
00:37:27,038 --> 00:37:29,580
then probably so is everyone else.

720
00:37:29,920 --> 00:37:32,502
If you use that data, they're going to as well,

721
00:37:32,802 --> 00:37:33,803
and you're probably going to end up

722
00:37:33,843 --> 00:37:34,984
with really similar results.

723
00:37:35,784 --> 00:37:37,125
You're going to make a copycat.

724
00:37:37,846 --> 00:37:40,168
You're going to go and you're going to make Perry Mason.

725
00:37:40,928 --> 00:37:43,410
And remember, that key component is the human touch,

726
00:37:43,731 --> 00:37:45,132
and that's Netflix's secret,

727
00:37:45,252 --> 00:37:47,113
one that they guard very closely.

728
00:37:47,594 --> 00:37:49,735
What human influence do they put on their data?

729
00:37:50,316 --> 00:37:51,276
How is it interpreted?

730
00:37:52,057 --> 00:37:55,099
How did they get from Perry Mason to House of Cards?

731
00:37:56,061 --> 00:37:57,142
I don't know, they won't say.

732
00:37:58,323 --> 00:38:00,965
One can assume that they followed the logical associations

733
00:38:01,085 --> 00:38:04,347
of character archetypes and themes and things like that,

734
00:38:04,868 --> 00:38:06,609
but the specifics of that process,

735
00:38:06,689 --> 00:38:08,971
how they combine their data with their instincts

736
00:38:09,511 --> 00:38:11,633
is part of the secret sauce that makes them special.

737
00:38:12,992 --> 00:38:16,153
This is the same design instinct that makes you special too.

738
00:38:16,793 --> 00:38:19,834
You can use data to inform your process,

739
00:38:20,334 --> 00:38:22,975
but don't let it lead you blindly into a decision,

740
00:38:23,355 --> 00:38:26,116
or you'll just end up making another copycat.

741
00:38:26,376 --> 00:38:29,657
You'll make the same level as everyone else over and over.

742
00:38:30,978 --> 00:38:33,259
So, throughout the history of the Gears franchise,

743
00:38:33,819 --> 00:38:35,920
we struggled with balancing our shotgun.

744
00:38:36,715 --> 00:38:39,958
Every single time we looked at the stats, the Nasher was at the top,

745
00:38:40,278 --> 00:38:44,722
sometimes responsible for as much as 90% of all kills in a given month.

746
00:38:45,983 --> 00:38:46,723
That's broken.

747
00:38:47,877 --> 00:38:48,817
So we tried to fix it.

748
00:38:49,437 --> 00:38:51,478
And every time we tried to fix it, we messed it up.

749
00:38:51,958 --> 00:38:53,759
Our player base kept yelling at us.

750
00:38:53,799 --> 00:38:56,440
They kept being upset, saying we just didn't understand.

751
00:38:57,021 --> 00:38:58,381
But we continued to watch the data,

752
00:38:58,621 --> 00:39:00,202
and we shared everything with them.

753
00:39:00,562 --> 00:39:02,343
We made these big presentations like this one

754
00:39:02,383 --> 00:39:04,444
that tried to explain the changes we were making,

755
00:39:04,784 --> 00:39:06,825
and we buried them and ourselves

756
00:39:06,945 --> 00:39:09,246
under mountains and mountains of data.

757
00:39:09,706 --> 00:39:12,287
We did range, we did kill counts, we did damage values,

758
00:39:12,328 --> 00:39:14,549
we analyzed the pellet distribution patterns.

759
00:39:14,569 --> 00:39:15,209
We did everything.

760
00:39:15,940 --> 00:39:18,022
but we never added that human touch.

761
00:39:18,602 --> 00:39:22,886
We never stopped to ask why people were using the shotgun in the first place.

762
00:39:23,586 --> 00:39:29,211
We had no end goal, no idea of what a fixed shotgun would actually look like.

763
00:39:30,432 --> 00:39:32,734
And as it turns out, the Nasher wasn't broken.

764
00:39:33,622 --> 00:39:37,906
It was this huge passion for how it felt to move through the map with the Nasher at your side.

765
00:39:38,446 --> 00:39:42,870
Firing the gun was fun, the effects and the sounds were satisfying,

766
00:39:43,331 --> 00:39:45,433
connecting with it was totally empowering.

767
00:39:45,893 --> 00:39:50,717
Using the Nasher was a hugely successful and rewarding experience.

768
00:39:51,398 --> 00:39:55,001
From a design perspective, it was achieving every goal that we were striving for.

769
00:39:55,842 --> 00:39:57,063
It was meaningful.

770
00:39:58,127 --> 00:40:01,149
It was all the other weapons that were completely deficient.

771
00:40:01,830 --> 00:40:03,371
And it wasn't until the third game in the series

772
00:40:03,411 --> 00:40:05,212
that I think we really started to realize this

773
00:40:05,612 --> 00:40:08,374
and truly appreciate what was going on.

774
00:40:09,015 --> 00:40:10,896
This was our ghost in the machine.

775
00:40:11,497 --> 00:40:13,598
We had all the information in the world about the Nasher

776
00:40:13,638 --> 00:40:16,460
and tons of really pretty charts and graphs to look at,

777
00:40:17,201 --> 00:40:18,261
but we were attached to them.

778
00:40:18,602 --> 00:40:21,163
And they prevented us from seeing the real problems

779
00:40:21,744 --> 00:40:23,845
because we had all these cool looking charts

780
00:40:23,885 --> 00:40:25,506
and there was so much information there

781
00:40:25,546 --> 00:40:26,627
that we couldn't get through it.

782
00:40:27,462 --> 00:40:33,244
We saw a problem in weapon balance, but we had no idea the solution that we were looking for.

783
00:40:33,724 --> 00:40:36,925
There was no defined state of success.

784
00:40:38,685 --> 00:40:43,487
So, in Gears of War Judgment, we were finally able to address this in what I think was a meaningful way.

785
00:40:43,967 --> 00:40:52,149
And with all of our weapons balanced equally, we toyed with the idea of giving everyone one single base weapon to start with,

786
00:40:52,269 --> 00:40:54,170
the Lancer rifle, and nothing else.

787
00:40:55,697 --> 00:40:57,558
All the other weapons, including the Gnasher,

788
00:40:57,978 --> 00:40:59,918
were scattered throughout the map as pickups.

789
00:41:00,578 --> 00:41:04,159
And because each weapon was now equally worthwhile,

790
00:41:04,559 --> 00:41:06,000
they were all worth searching for.

791
00:41:06,980 --> 00:41:08,800
And this gave the game a little bit more

792
00:41:08,820 --> 00:41:11,701
of an old school shooter feel, which is great.

793
00:41:12,081 --> 00:41:13,241
But at the end of the day, we wanted

794
00:41:13,281 --> 00:41:15,062
to give our players more choice.

795
00:41:15,102 --> 00:41:17,382
We wanted them to have some customization

796
00:41:17,442 --> 00:41:18,423
and personalization.

797
00:41:18,923 --> 00:41:23,424
So we decided to move to kind of a more modern feeling loadout

798
00:41:23,484 --> 00:41:23,724
model.

799
00:41:28,074 --> 00:41:29,756
Knowing our players affinity for the Nasher,

800
00:41:30,596 --> 00:41:33,098
it was being used as a lure in that original model

801
00:41:33,158 --> 00:41:36,081
so that we had shotguns scattered all over the map

802
00:41:36,141 --> 00:41:38,062
and people would go to all four corners

803
00:41:38,123 --> 00:41:40,424
and you can see a nice, even distribution of play.

804
00:41:42,626 --> 00:41:44,228
After we changed to the loadout system,

805
00:41:44,848 --> 00:41:47,971
our players immediately fell back into patterns of camping

806
00:41:48,351 --> 00:41:50,993
that plagued all the previous iterations of Gears.

807
00:41:52,154 --> 00:41:55,297
Now, our heat map showed people moving and dying

808
00:41:55,397 --> 00:41:56,898
in these tight, collected groups.

809
00:41:58,088 --> 00:42:01,909
And we started to question if we had really addressed those problems in weapon balance,

810
00:42:01,989 --> 00:42:02,850
why was this happening?

811
00:42:03,930 --> 00:42:08,311
Well, in contrast to our previous games, Judgment maps were all asymmetrical.

812
00:42:09,011 --> 00:42:15,253
Rather than a single individual front that pulled players to a common ground, every point

813
00:42:15,293 --> 00:42:17,554
in the map had to be a defensible front.

814
00:42:18,454 --> 00:42:22,675
And since players were now starting with their favorite weapon, the gnasher, and they could

815
00:42:22,775 --> 00:42:26,596
use it effectively everywhere, why would you ever leave?

816
00:42:27,218 --> 00:42:30,259
Why not just spawn, wait for somebody to run up to you and shoot them in the face?

817
00:42:30,399 --> 00:42:31,379
You didn't have to go anywhere.

818
00:42:31,399 --> 00:42:32,539
This is exactly what they did.

819
00:42:32,880 --> 00:42:34,660
They all started camping.

820
00:42:36,481 --> 00:42:40,562
This was, of course, a fixable problem, and it led to some overhaul on a few of our maps.

821
00:42:40,602 --> 00:42:44,763
This is the overhead from the map called Gondola, if you're at all familiar with this series.

822
00:42:45,323 --> 00:42:48,945
And we had to add some extra access points to the top of the map

823
00:42:49,405 --> 00:42:52,626
and open up this kind of highly defensible side area

824
00:42:52,926 --> 00:42:55,046
because those two areas were really easy to camp.

825
00:42:56,163 --> 00:42:59,427
Of course, this also meant that we had to rearrange our weapon loadouts,

826
00:42:59,547 --> 00:43:02,010
add some extra escape paths down from the bottom,

827
00:43:02,750 --> 00:43:03,932
rework some approaches,

828
00:43:04,152 --> 00:43:06,315
move a couple walls to accommodate other changes,

829
00:43:06,395 --> 00:43:08,837
open up lines of sight, on and on.

830
00:43:08,858 --> 00:43:13,142
It was this endless cascade of issues that we were completely unprepared for.

831
00:43:13,903 --> 00:43:15,826
And this was only one map.

832
00:43:16,810 --> 00:43:22,373
Just like data without context, change without defined purpose is meaningless.

833
00:43:22,834 --> 00:43:27,096
It can only lead to churn, wasting time and resources.

834
00:43:27,796 --> 00:43:31,518
We rebalanced all of the other weapons in the game to accommodate the shotgun.

835
00:43:32,219 --> 00:43:34,660
And that changing, and then changing to the loadout model,

836
00:43:34,820 --> 00:43:36,941
was just one more small change in the system.

837
00:43:37,742 --> 00:43:41,844
But we were never able to address all the other problems that it created down the road.

838
00:43:42,344 --> 00:43:46,047
And the game always felt imbalanced and off as a result of that.

839
00:43:47,205 --> 00:43:53,607
Now, there's no question that our goal was absolutely to improve our players' experience.

840
00:43:55,488 --> 00:43:57,329
But how do you define what that actually is?

841
00:43:57,609 --> 00:44:00,410
There's no end, there's no measurable result there.

842
00:44:00,790 --> 00:44:06,071
There was no tangible goal and no understanding of the complexity of all the other systems

843
00:44:06,091 --> 00:44:07,772
that were involved in this process.

844
00:44:08,657 --> 00:44:13,142
We didn't address what we were building, we didn't address why we were making the change,

845
00:44:13,422 --> 00:44:16,165
and we didn't address who we were making those changes for.

846
00:44:16,806 --> 00:44:20,930
We changed just for the sake of change, and we ended up churning for months.

847
00:44:22,211 --> 00:44:25,976
And remember, no problem is ever, like this, is ever really 100% fixed.

848
00:44:28,934 --> 00:44:31,855
When we moved that boomshot in Academy, we didn't solve the problem.

849
00:44:32,416 --> 00:44:37,598
We created a new hypothesis, that players would move away from that area,

850
00:44:38,058 --> 00:44:41,340
and we found that the new data supported our new hypothesis.

851
00:44:41,980 --> 00:44:44,821
Statistically seeking, we saw that players were, on average,

852
00:44:44,881 --> 00:44:46,922
moving away from that area instead of camping it.

853
00:44:47,983 --> 00:44:51,224
Theoretically speaking, we could continue to test forever.

854
00:44:52,114 --> 00:44:53,995
You get more information every time you do it, right?

855
00:44:54,055 --> 00:44:55,236
You refine your hypothesis.

856
00:44:55,276 --> 00:44:56,637
You improve your probability space.

857
00:44:57,157 --> 00:44:59,699
It's not like that data is ever going to get old or be thrown

858
00:44:59,759 --> 00:45:00,079
away.

859
00:45:00,219 --> 00:45:00,999
It just piles up.

860
00:45:01,440 --> 00:45:04,061
But the reality is that at some point, you do need to stop.

861
00:45:04,341 --> 00:45:05,182
You have a schedule.

862
00:45:05,222 --> 00:45:06,022
You have a budget.

863
00:45:06,342 --> 00:45:08,424
And you have all these other things that need prioritization.

864
00:45:08,444 --> 00:45:11,986
In complicated systems, like a multiplayer game,

865
00:45:12,406 --> 00:45:15,488
there's always the chance that the results of your next play

866
00:45:15,528 --> 00:45:19,630
test are going to reveal a new ghost in the machine.

867
00:45:20,622 --> 00:45:22,343
So at some point, you need to stop.

868
00:45:22,463 --> 00:45:27,446
You need to accept that you know the best that you can know right now and move on.

869
00:45:28,526 --> 00:45:35,209
In order to avoid churn, in order to keep from chasing ghosts, you need to outline your

870
00:45:35,249 --> 00:45:37,731
goals and define success from the start.

871
00:45:41,933 --> 00:45:42,993
All right, cool stories, bro.

872
00:45:43,133 --> 00:45:44,254
What do I do with all this information?

873
00:45:45,888 --> 00:45:51,390
Good design is very often about simplification, streamlining, and clarification.

874
00:45:52,251 --> 00:45:56,693
I look at analytics as a mindset that helps me focus on those principles

875
00:45:57,173 --> 00:46:02,076
and use them to inform the decisions that I make every single day.

876
00:46:02,995 --> 00:46:08,658
Continuing to ask why strengthens the impact and validity of every decision that we make.

877
00:46:09,198 --> 00:46:13,740
It helps focus on what you're building and how you should approach it, and this helps

878
00:46:13,800 --> 00:46:15,241
us to define our goals.

879
00:46:15,881 --> 00:46:19,563
And once change is made, it can be quantified and measured.

880
00:46:20,043 --> 00:46:25,105
This separates opinions from information and leads to meaningful change in your maps.

881
00:46:27,052 --> 00:46:29,834
And remember, there are no guarantees.

882
00:46:30,294 --> 00:46:33,617
One of the most famous sayings in Hollywood comes from screenwriter William Goldman,

883
00:46:33,917 --> 00:46:36,259
who says, nobody knows anything.

884
00:46:36,559 --> 00:46:41,142
Not one person in the entire motion picture field knows for certainty what's going to work.

885
00:46:41,723 --> 00:46:43,104
Every time out, it's a guess.

886
00:46:44,065 --> 00:46:49,148
This is why people passed on Raiders of the Lost Ark, and Star Wars, and Harry Potter,

887
00:46:49,389 --> 00:46:52,531
and the Twilight series, all predicting their inevitable failure.

888
00:46:53,735 --> 00:46:56,736
Failures just like those goofy kids that started Microsoft,

889
00:46:57,176 --> 00:46:58,797
and Apple, and Epic Games.

890
00:47:00,177 --> 00:47:03,178
But reality is, games do fail every day.

891
00:47:03,218 --> 00:47:03,998
It's bound to happen.

892
00:47:04,398 --> 00:47:06,979
Temple Run was this huge success right out of the gates.

893
00:47:07,819 --> 00:47:10,100
But you have to remember that they were an anomaly.

894
00:47:10,660 --> 00:47:14,781
It's more telling that Rovio had 56 other games

895
00:47:14,881 --> 00:47:15,941
before Angry Birds.

896
00:47:16,481 --> 00:47:18,882
And that Candy Crush, the number one game in the world,

897
00:47:19,462 --> 00:47:20,802
was more than 150th in King's roster.

898
00:47:24,019 --> 00:47:25,621
So it's really easy to look back and say,

899
00:47:25,641 --> 00:47:26,883
yeah, this is what we did right,

900
00:47:26,923 --> 00:47:27,984
or that's what they did right.

901
00:47:28,525 --> 00:47:30,608
But it's even harder to look forward

902
00:47:30,889 --> 00:47:34,053
and predict this is what we should be doing.

903
00:47:35,355 --> 00:47:36,597
Because there are no guarantees.

904
00:47:37,391 --> 00:47:40,692
But analytics can improve your chances for success.

905
00:47:40,732 --> 00:47:42,553
They help you both understand your players

906
00:47:42,993 --> 00:47:45,374
and the content that those players are consuming,

907
00:47:45,934 --> 00:47:48,695
the content you are building for your players.

908
00:47:49,236 --> 00:47:51,116
The better you understand your own maps,

909
00:47:51,616 --> 00:47:53,577
the better you can predict the way people

910
00:47:53,837 --> 00:47:54,898
will interact with them,

911
00:47:55,318 --> 00:47:56,838
and the better you'll be able to innovate

912
00:47:57,039 --> 00:47:58,599
and come up with new and interesting

913
00:47:58,839 --> 00:48:00,400
and meaningful surprises.

914
00:48:01,120 --> 00:48:03,741
The cycle of innovation and experimentation

915
00:48:04,241 --> 00:48:06,062
is how you magic band your maps.

916
00:48:06,932 --> 00:48:09,453
Experimentation is the foundation for analytics,

917
00:48:09,813 --> 00:48:13,434
in the same way that iteration is the foundation for design.

918
00:48:14,755 --> 00:48:16,335
This is Six Sigma.

919
00:48:16,936 --> 00:48:19,277
It's an analytical model that was

920
00:48:19,317 --> 00:48:20,997
designed for the manufacturing industry.

921
00:48:21,898 --> 00:48:23,578
It's this weird process that requires

922
00:48:23,618 --> 00:48:26,079
like training and certification, and I don't have any of it.

923
00:48:26,480 --> 00:48:28,460
But when I saw this, it struck me

924
00:48:29,021 --> 00:48:32,622
how similar the methodology is to level design.

925
00:48:33,742 --> 00:48:35,963
Start at the top right and look at the defined state.

926
00:48:36,825 --> 00:48:37,525
What are you building?

927
00:48:38,266 --> 00:48:39,067
Why are you building it?

928
00:48:39,127 --> 00:48:40,108
Who are you building it for?

929
00:48:40,168 --> 00:48:42,630
Does it support a game system or the narrative?

930
00:48:43,551 --> 00:48:44,412
What are your goals?

931
00:48:44,532 --> 00:48:45,933
What are you trying to achieve?

932
00:48:46,474 --> 00:48:48,976
Outline your goals and define your success.

933
00:48:50,800 --> 00:48:52,382
and then go on to measure.

934
00:48:53,002 --> 00:48:54,383
With a clear outlining of your goals,

935
00:48:54,423 --> 00:48:56,064
you can define your starting point.

936
00:48:56,204 --> 00:48:57,385
If you know where you are now,

937
00:48:57,485 --> 00:48:59,367
you can measure where you're gonna be later.

938
00:48:59,847 --> 00:49:01,028
This is metrics.

939
00:49:01,749 --> 00:49:03,050
Maybe you're introducing a new weapon

940
00:49:03,090 --> 00:49:04,371
and you wanna track success.

941
00:49:04,431 --> 00:49:06,712
Maybe there's some important visualization

942
00:49:06,853 --> 00:49:09,755
or a visual element like a tower

943
00:49:09,815 --> 00:49:11,296
and you wanna use heat maps to track

944
00:49:11,616 --> 00:49:13,237
where and when people are getting there.

945
00:49:14,037 --> 00:49:16,219
Just remember that once you have this data,

946
00:49:16,359 --> 00:49:18,741
it still needs to be interpreted and analyzed.

947
00:49:19,222 --> 00:49:20,423
Data is information.

948
00:49:20,643 --> 00:49:21,944
It is not answers.

949
00:49:23,385 --> 00:49:24,847
So then you analyze.

950
00:49:24,887 --> 00:49:25,607
Cover your bases.

951
00:49:26,048 --> 00:49:28,070
Don't just accept that first answer that pops up.

952
00:49:28,450 --> 00:49:30,011
Maybe players are dying frequently

953
00:49:30,071 --> 00:49:31,112
around a powerful weapon.

954
00:49:31,773 --> 00:49:34,195
But maybe there's other factors, like map geometry.

955
00:49:35,056 --> 00:49:37,338
Separate correlation and causation.

956
00:49:38,573 --> 00:49:40,675
One of the biggest lessons I've learned as a designer

957
00:49:40,955 --> 00:49:44,758
is that if I need to repeatedly defend a design decision

958
00:49:45,879 --> 00:49:49,422
with my team, with my players, it's probably a bad decision.

959
00:49:50,042 --> 00:49:53,505
And that's especially true if the information

960
00:49:53,545 --> 00:49:58,248
that I'm using to support that decision is pure statistics.

961
00:49:59,349 --> 00:50:01,651
There's always going to be people who don't immediately get.

962
00:50:02,684 --> 00:50:04,806
a change that you make or a design decision that you make.

963
00:50:05,087 --> 00:50:06,588
But if they don't get it quickly,

964
00:50:06,969 --> 00:50:08,431
through testing and iteration,

965
00:50:08,951 --> 00:50:10,533
you need to step back and ask why.

966
00:50:11,014 --> 00:50:13,557
What part of your design isn't being communicated?

967
00:50:14,117 --> 00:50:15,279
Question everything.

968
00:50:16,332 --> 00:50:20,877
Analytics don't give you answers, but they do improve your chances for success.

969
00:50:21,497 --> 00:50:24,420
You are the one who adds that human element.

970
00:50:24,941 --> 00:50:27,343
This is where we get to improve. This is your moment to shine.

971
00:50:27,363 --> 00:50:29,145
This is your role as an LD.

972
00:50:29,725 --> 00:50:31,487
Anyone can look at those data and read the numbers,

973
00:50:31,807 --> 00:50:35,811
but it's the designer's job to know how and when to incorporate that data

974
00:50:36,171 --> 00:50:39,495
to make a change that results in meaningful impact.

975
00:50:41,109 --> 00:50:42,350
And then finally, control.

976
00:50:42,790 --> 00:50:45,371
Understand that every change you make has consequences.

977
00:50:45,852 --> 00:50:47,312
Systems are complicated.

978
00:50:47,813 --> 00:50:49,754
Change one system, and it affects another.

979
00:50:50,314 --> 00:50:53,515
Always ask, what's the bigger impact of this small change?

980
00:50:53,936 --> 00:50:55,857
What's the goal of that change?

981
00:50:56,617 --> 00:50:57,397
Nothing is simple.

982
00:50:58,018 --> 00:50:58,998
Every change matters.

983
00:51:00,579 --> 00:51:01,420
And you're going to mess it up.

984
00:51:02,180 --> 00:51:03,861
But that's okay, that's part of the process.

985
00:51:04,201 --> 00:51:06,162
Be honest about it and learn from your mistakes.

986
00:51:06,202 --> 00:51:09,604
When you fail at something, go back, redefine, retest.

987
00:51:09,984 --> 00:51:13,427
This is exactly why this process is a continuous loop.

988
00:51:14,187 --> 00:51:16,889
You identify a question, you develop a hypothesis,

989
00:51:17,209 --> 00:51:19,070
you test, you measure, and you repeat.

990
00:51:19,710 --> 00:51:20,611
This is iteration.

991
00:51:21,311 --> 00:51:22,532
Every time the loop repeats,

992
00:51:22,592 --> 00:51:24,413
your chances of success get a little better.

993
00:51:24,814 --> 00:51:26,435
You improve your probability space.

994
00:51:27,848 --> 00:51:29,649
So much of science is about patterns.

995
00:51:30,210 --> 00:51:33,651
And as I've mentioned, analytics is about discovering those patterns.

996
00:51:34,352 --> 00:51:36,973
But there's patterns in non-science areas as well.

997
00:51:37,653 --> 00:51:38,574
Look at pop culture.

998
00:51:38,594 --> 00:51:42,876
A few years ago, we had shooter after shooter coming to the market,

999
00:51:43,236 --> 00:51:46,298
